-- Deals of the day- Mergers and acquisitions
-- 
-- Thu Jan 30, 2014 06:01AM EST
-- None



Jan 30 (Reuters) - The following bids, mergers, acquisitions and disposals were reported by 1100 GMT on Thursday:

** Australian retailer David Jones Ltd <DJS.AX> said it had rejected a takeover approach from Myer Holdings Ltd <MYR.AX> worth A$1.4 billion ($1.23 billion) in October 2013 and was no longer in talks. [ID:nL3N0L437F]  ** Glencore Xstrata Plc <GLEN.L> plans to sell its 62.5 percent stake in the $5.9 billion Tampakan copper and gold project, Indophil Resources N L <IRN.AX>, its partner in the long-delayed Philippines joint venture said. [ID:nL3N0L42P2]  ** European private-equity firm CVC Capital Partners Ltd [CVC.UL] is nearing a deal to invest in antivirus software developer Avast Software, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. CVC Capital is set to take a significant minority stake that would value Prague-based Avast at roughly $1 billion, including debt, the sources said. [ID:nL3N0L41V0]  ** Russian telecoms group Rostelecom <RTKM.MM> is planning to sell a 12 percent stake to banking group VTB Bank OAO <VTBR.MM> for up to 35 billion roubles ($995 million), to help to pay for a share buyback, business daily Kommersant reported. [ID:nL5N0L41CK]  ** Dassault Systemes SA <DAST.PA> has agreed to buy U.S. scientific software firm Accelrys Inc <ACCL.O> in an all-cash deal valuing the San-Diego company at about $750 million, as it seeks to expand its product portfolio, the software company said. [ID:nL5N0L40G6]  ** Japanese systems integrator NEC Corp <6701.T> said it has agreed to sell its Internet provider NEC Biglobe to Japan Industrial Partners and would book a special profit of about 27 billion yen ($264 million) on the sale in the current business year to March. [ID:nT9N0KP018]  ** Turkey's largest food group, Yildiz Holding, has signed a deal to sell its yeast-making unit Dosu Maya to French company Le Saffre for $220 million, Yildiz Chairman Murat Ulker said. [ID:nL5N0L40ZD]  ** Lenovo Group Ltd <0992.HK> said on Wednesday that it agreed to buy Google Inc's <GOOG.O> Motorola handset division for $2.91 billion, in what is China's largest-ever tech deal as Lenovo buys its way into the heavily competitive U.S. handset market dominated by Apple Inc <AAPL.O>. [ID:nL2N0L329M]  ** The head of Pirelli & C SpA <PECI.MI> said on Wednesday that he had received no proposal regarding a possible sale of the Italian tyremaker. [ID:nI6N0KJ04J]  ** U.S. power company ContourGlobal said on Wednesday it will acquire three hydroelectric power plants in Armenia in a $250 million deal. [ID:nL5N0L33U3]  ($1 = 102.2500 Japanese yen) ($1 = 1.1425 Australian dollars)